{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "Architecture Overview",
  "description": "A guided walk through llm-valet's two parallel abstractions — resources (machine monitoring) and providers (LLM serving) — and how they meet in the watchdog and API.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 57,
      "pattern": "class ResourceCollector(ABC):",
      "title": "1 · Two parallel abstractions",
      "description": "The whole system is built on two symmetric [Abstract Base Classes](https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html): `ResourceCollector` and `LLMProvider`.\n\n`ResourceCollector` (here) monitors the machine — RAM, CPU, GPU, disk.\n\n`LLMProvider` (in `providers/base.py`) is the abstraction layer for local LLM serving software. Any provider that can be paused, resumed, started, and stopped can be implemented as a concrete subclass — Ollama ships in v1.0, with LM Studio, vLLM, exo, KoboldCPP, and others as natural future targets. The rest of the system (watchdog, API) only ever calls the `LLMProvider` interface, so swapping or adding a provider requires no changes outside its own file.\n\nNeither ABC depends on the other. The watchdog wires them together."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 10,
      "pattern": "class PressureLevel(enum.Enum):",
      "title": "2 · Metric dataclasses",
      "description": "`PressureLevel` + the four metric dataclasses (`MemoryMetrics`, `CPUMetrics`, `GPUMetrics`, `DiskMetrics`) are the currency of the system — every decision downstream is made from a single `SystemMetrics` snapshot.\n\n**Occupancy vs. demand — why both exist**\n\n`used_pct` measures *occupancy*: how much of the RAM pool is in use. `PressureLevel` measures *demand*: whether processes are actively competing for memory the OS can't readily supply. These are not the same thing, and on macOS they frequently diverge. The OS deliberately fills RAM with file caches and pre-warmed apps — 90% occupancy can coexist with `NORMAL` pressure because nothing is actually contesting that memory. Pressure only rises when the OS has to make a painful tradeoff: compress pages, evict a cache, or delay an allocation. On Apple Silicon the distinction matters even more, because CPU and GPU draw from the same unified pool — pressure reflects demand across both.\n\n**Cross-platform grounding**\n\n- **macOS**: native kernel API (`memory_pressure` CLI), reports `normal / warn / critical` directly.\n- **Linux**: PSI (Pressure Stall Information, `/proc/pressure/memory`) measures how long tasks stall waiting for memory — the closest Linux equivalent, though availability varies by kernel version.\n- **Windows**: no native demand signal. `PressureLevel` is derived from `used_pct` thresholds in `_pressure_from_pct()` (`resources/windows.py`): `< 75%` → `NORMAL`, `≥ 75%` → `WARN`, `≥ 90%` → `CRITICAL`. These are currently hardcoded and independent of the user's `ram_pause_pct` config — a future Windows implementation pass should make them user-adjustable to match the config-driven approach on other platforms.\n\n**Optional fields**\n\nSome metrics simply don't exist on every machine. `GPUMetrics` fields like `vram_used_mb` and `compute_pct` are typed `int | None` or `float | None` — Python's notation for \"this value may be absent.\" On a machine with no accessible GPU driver, those fields are `None` rather than a misleading zero. Callers check `supported_metrics()` first to know which fields are safe to use."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 101,
      "pattern": "class ThresholdEngine:",
      "title": "3 · ThresholdEngine: pure logic, no I/O",
      "description": "`ThresholdEngine` is pure logic — no network calls, no filesystem reads, no `psutil`. It stores `ResourceThresholds` (configuration), but holds no runtime state. All counters and timers belong to the watchdog.\n\n**Two methods, two responsibilities**\n\n`evaluate()` answers *should we pause?* — returns `(True, reason)` if any metric breaches its pause threshold. `evaluate_resume()` answers *is it safe to resume?* — returns `(True, reason)` only when all metrics are below their resume thresholds.\n\nThey're separate because the watchdog applies different time-window logic to each: `evaluate()` results are accumulated across ticks for the CPU sustained-seconds window; `evaluate_resume()` results gate the grace-period check. A single method would force the caller to re-derive which direction it was checking.\n\n**Hysteresis: asymmetric pause and resume thresholds**\n\nRAM pauses at `ram_pause_pct` (default 85%) but resumes only below `ram_resume_pct` (default 60%). The 25-point gap prevents the model from thrashing — loading back in at 84% would immediately re-trigger the pause. CPU and GPU don't need a separate resume threshold in config: the watchdog's grace period provides the equivalent buffer for CPU, and the gap between GPU load and VRAM usage is typically large enough that a single threshold suffices.\n\n**CPU sustained-seconds lives in the watchdog, not here**\n\n`evaluate()` returns `True` whenever `cpu.used_pct >= cpu_pause_pct` — it does not count ticks. The watchdog increments a counter each `check_interval` while `evaluate()` returns True, and only calls `provider.pause()` when `counter × check_interval >= cpu_sustained_seconds`. RAM and GPU bypass the sustained window — they trigger immediately.\n\n**Testability**\n\nPass a crafted `SystemMetrics`, assert the decision. No mocking needed; no OS access possible."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 88,
      "pattern": "ram_resume_pct: float = 60.0",
      "title": "4 · Hysteresis: preventing pause/resume oscillation",
      "description": "`ram_resume_pct` is intentionally lower than `ram_pause_pct` — this gap is called **hysteresis**, borrowed from control theory.\n\n**What oscillation looks like without it**\n\nSuppose the LLM model uses ~5 GB on a 16 GB machine (31% RAM). With a single threshold at 85%:\n\n1. External pressure pushes RAM to 86% → watchdog pauses — model evicted → RAM drops to ~55%\n2. Resources look fine → watchdog resumes — model reloads → RAM climbs back to ~86%\n3. Loop restarts immediately\n\nThe model spends all its time loading and unloading, never serving inference.\n\n**How the gap fixes it**\n\nWith the default 85%/60% pair, the resume gate only opens below 60%. After eviction, RAM falls to ~55% (safely below 60%), so resume is allowed. Once the model reloads, its footprint pushes RAM to ~86% — above the 60% resume floor but below the 85% pause threshold. The model stays loaded until *external* pressure climbs again.\n\n**Choosing the gap**\n\nNo single value is universally correct — it depends on the model's RAM footprint. A gap of 20–25 percentage points is a reasonable starting point. Too narrow and oscillation returns; too wide and resume is delayed long after resources are genuinely free. There is no formula that works for every model and machine combination — tune `ram_resume_pct` based on your model size and observed behavior.\n\nThe worst case is when the model *is* the dominant RAM consumer: loading it will always push RAM above the resume floor. `auto_resume_on_ram_pressure: false` disables auto-resume for RAM-triggered pauses entirely, requiring a manual `/resume`. This is the escape hatch for that scenario."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 126,
      "pattern": "NOTE — memory_pressure level is intentionally NOT used as an independent",
      "title": "5 · Apple Silicon: why memory_pressure is NOT a trigger (by design)",
      "description": "On Apple Silicon, loading a large model into unified memory routinely causes transient `CRITICAL` pressure readings — even when RAM% is within the user's configured threshold. If `memory_pressure CRITICAL` were used as an independent pause trigger, every model load would immediately pause the service.\n\nSo `PressureLevel` is reported in `/metrics` for informational purposes only. `ram_pause_pct` (from config) is the authoritative trigger.\n\n**The limitation this introduces**\n\nPressure captures signals that RAM% cannot: memory bandwidth saturation, paging activity, and the kernel's own assessment of whether the system is struggling to satisfy memory demand. A machine at 80% RAM under heavy GPU inference pressure can be more stressed than one at 85% with an idle model — and the current design treats them identically.\n\nThe natural fix is a sustained-pressure window mirroring the CPU `sustained_seconds` pattern: require N consecutive `CRITICAL` readings before acting, long enough to outlast model-loading transients. This was evaluated but explicitly deferred.\n\n**Decision — jp@legionforge.org, 2026-04-27**\n\n`PressureLevel` is excluded from pause trigger logic through at least v0.6.0 and v1.0. Reasons:\n\n- The current design is tested and working. A pressure sensitivity threshold adds a new configurable parameter without an empirically grounded default — the loading-transient duration on M-series hardware has not been measured.\n- Pressure is platform-inconsistent: macOS reports it natively via the `memory_pressure` CLI; Linux uses PSI (`/proc/pressure/memory`, kernel-version dependent); Windows has no native signal and derives `PressureLevel` from hardcoded RAM% thresholds in `resources/windows.py`. A pressure trigger would behave fundamentally differently across platforms before cross-platform parity is validated.\n\nFurther study is planned. When revisited: add `pressure_critical_sustained_seconds: int` to `ResourceThresholds`, accumulate ticks in the watchdog (same pattern as `_cpu_pressure_ticks`), and gate the trigger to platforms where `\"pressure\" in collector.supported_metrics()` — preventing Windows divergence and giving operators a window to filter model-loading transients."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/providers/base.py",
      "line": 24,
      "pattern": "class LLMProvider(ABC):",
      "title": "6 · LLMProvider: the other half",
      "description": "`LLMProvider` is the contract every provider implementation must satisfy.\n\n**pause/resume vs. start/stop**\n\nThe critical distinction: **pause** unloads the model from memory but leaves the service running (fast — seconds). **stop** shuts the service down entirely (slow — 30–90s to come back). The watchdog only ever calls `pause`/`resume`; `start`/`stop` are reserved for the API's manual control surface.\n\n**Model management surface**\n\nBeyond lifecycle control, the ABC includes a model management surface: `list_models()`, `load_model()`, `delete_model()`, `pull_model()`, and `force_pause()`. These back the `/models` family of API endpoints and the model selector in the WebUI.\n\n`force_pause()` is distinct from `pause()`: instead of using Ollama's `keep_alive=0` eviction (which can be blocked by an active inference request), it kills the `ollama_llama_runner` subprocess directly — immediately interrupting inference without stopping the Ollama service itself. It is exposed as `POST /pause/force` and is also called by `POST /stop/force`. Regular `POST /pause` and the watchdog both use the graceful `pause()`. In the WebUI, the force pause button appears automatically after a pause or stop has been initiated but the model appears stuck — it is not visible during normal operation.\n\n**Extended dataclasses**\n\n`ModelInfo` carries the name, disk size, and max context length of each locally available model — populated from `/api/tags` + `/api/show`. `ProviderStatus` gained two optional fields: `size_vram_mb` (the GPU portion of the model's memory footprint from `/api/ps`) and `loaded_context_length` (the active context window, cached before eviction so `resume()` can restore it).\n\nOllama is the only concrete implementation. `LM Studio`, `vLLM`, and `MLX` are post-v1.0 parked features."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 14,
      "pattern": "class WatchdogState(enum.Enum):",
      "title": "7 · FSM: five states",
      "description": "The watchdog is a five-state machine:\n\n```\nRUNNING → PAUSING → PAUSED → RESUMING → RUNNING\n   │           ↕        │        ↕\n   │        RUNNING   PAUSED  PAUSED\n   │       (on fail) (on fail)\n   │                  │\n   └──────────────────┴──→ PROVIDER_DOWN → RUNNING\n```\n\n**Stable states:** `RUNNING`, `PAUSED`, `PROVIDER_DOWN`\n\n**Transient states:** `PAUSING` and `RESUMING` exist only while the provider call is in-flight — `_tick()` awaits those transitions inline, so they are never visible at tick entry under normal operation. Crucially, they are self-healing on failure:\n\n- `pause()` fails → `PAUSING` reverts to `RUNNING`\n- `resume()` fails → `RESUMING` reverts to `PAUSED`\n\nThe system never gets stuck in a transient state.\n\n**`PROVIDER_DOWN`** is entered from either `RUNNING` or `PAUSED` when the health probe detects that Ollama has crashed. The watchdog does not attempt to restart Ollama — it polls `health_check()` passively each tick and waits for the provider to return on its own (restarted by launchd on Homebrew installs, or manually by the user on Ollama.app installs). Recovery always exits to `RUNNING`, not the prior state — a crash during a natural pause clears the pause.\n\n**Recovery fall-through:** when `PROVIDER_DOWN` resolves, the code falls through and evaluates resources immediately on the same tick. If resources are already critical, the watchdog can chain `PROVIDER_DOWN → RUNNING → PAUSING → PAUSED` within a single `_tick()` call."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 34,
      "pattern": "self._provider = provider",
      "title": "8 · Watchdog constructor: composed, not coupled",
      "description": "The watchdog receives a `LLMProvider` and a `ResourceCollector` by injection. It never calls `psutil` for resource data — that goes through `collector.collect()` — and it never imports a concrete provider.\n\nThe one place `psutil` does appear in `watchdog.py` is `_detect_game()`, which calls `psutil.process_iter()` to scan for `steamapps/common` paths. Game detection is process enumeration, not resource measurement, so it doesn't belong in `ResourceCollector`.\n\nThis keeps the watchdog testable: swap in mock implementations of `LLMProvider` and `ResourceCollector` and assert state transitions without touching the OS or a real Ollama instance. `ThresholdEngine` is constructed internally because it's pure logic with no external surface."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 78,
      "pattern": "def notify_manual_pause(self) -> None:",
      "title": "9 · Manual pause sync — why this exists",
      "description": "`notify_manual_pause()` and `notify_manual_resume()` are called by the API after a successful `/pause` or `/resume` request.\n\nWithout these, the FSM and the provider are out of sync: the user manually pauses, but the watchdog still thinks the state is `RUNNING` and will try to pause again on the next tick — or worse, immediately resume because resources look fine.\n\nThe API writes the outcome; the watchdog syncs its view to match. This is the handshake that keeps both state machines coherent."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 101,
      "pattern": "async def _tick(self) -> None:",
      "title": "10 · The tick: where everything meets",
      "description": "Every `check_interval_seconds`, `_tick()` runs this sequence:\n\n1. Health-probe the provider — detect unexpected crashes → `PROVIDER_DOWN`\n2. `collector.collect()` → `SystemMetrics`\n3. `_detect_game()` → scan psutil for `steamapps/common` processes\n4. `ThresholdEngine.evaluate(metrics)` → `(resource_pressure, reason)`\n5. Accumulate CPU ticks for the sustained-seconds window\n6. Resolve `should_pause` — game OR (resource pressure AND not CPU-only-or-not-yet-sustained)\n7. If `RUNNING` and `should_pause` → record `_pause_trigger` (ram/cpu/gpu/game) → `_transition_to_paused()`\n8. If `PAUSED` and not `should_pause` → `ThresholdEngine.evaluate_resume(metrics)` → if `_pause_trigger == \"ram\"` and `auto_resume_on_ram_pressure is False` → return (require manual `/resume`) → if safe and grace period elapsed → `_transition_to_running()`"
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/api.py",
      "line": 191,
      "pattern": "T2 — DNS rebinding: reject any Host header not in the allowlist.",
      "title": "11 · Security middleware: order matters",
      "description": "Three middleware layers protect the API. Understanding their execution order requires knowing how Starlette stacks them: each `add_middleware()` call *prepends* to the internal list, so the **last call is outermost** — it executes first on every incoming request.\n\nRegistration order in the source (first to last): `TrustedHostMiddleware`, body size limit, `CORSMiddleware`.\n\nExecution order on an incoming request (outermost to innermost):\n\n1. **[CORSMiddleware](https://www.starlette.io/middleware/#corsmiddleware)** (last-added, outermost) — handles preflight (`OPTIONS`) requests and injects `Access-Control-*` headers. `allow_origins` is empty by default — no cross-origin access unless explicitly configured (T3). An empty list means same-origin only, the secure default; `allow_origins=[\"*\"]` would allow any website's JavaScript to reach the API from any domain.\n2. **Body size limit** (middle) — a custom `@app.middleware(\"http\")` decorator, not a Starlette built-in (Starlette ships no body-size guard). Drains and buffers the request stream; rejects anything over 64 KB before JSON parsing. `Content-Length` alone is insufficient because chunked transfer encoding omits it.\n3. **[TrustedHostMiddleware](https://www.starlette.io/middleware/#trustedhostmiddleware)** (first-added, innermost) — rejects any `Host` header not in the allowlist before the request reaches a route handler (T2 — DNS rebinding). Without this, a malicious web page can rebind its DNS to `127.0.0.1` and make browser requests that appear local. The allowlist (`localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, `*.local`, plus any LAN IPs when bound to `0.0.0.0`) is the explicit boundary.\n\n**Why these three and not others:** Authentication lives at the dependency layer (`require_api_key`) rather than as a fourth middleware — this lets the setup endpoints (`/setup/*`) opt out cleanly without special-casing middleware logic. Rate limiting is per-endpoint rather than middleware because different endpoints have different limits and cooldowns. IP allowlisting is not used; the `X-API-Key` requirement for non-localhost traffic provides the equivalent gate without maintaining a static list.\n\n`TrustedHostMiddleware` does not need to be outermost to block DNS rebinding — it only needs to run before any handler, which it does regardless of its position in the stack. The body size check runs before host validation to drop oversized requests cheaply."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/api.py",
      "line": 263,
      "pattern": "async def require_api_key(",
      "title": "12 · Auth: localhost exempt, LAN requires key",
      "description": "`require_api_key` is injected as a FastAPI dependency on all schema-visible endpoints — both read-only GETs (`/status`, `/watchdog`, `/metrics`, `/models`, `/config`) and mutating operations. Only hidden endpoints (setup flow, `/`, `/favicon.ico`) omit it.\n\nRequests from `127.0.0.1` or `::1` bypass the key check entirely — if you're local, you're trusted. Any other source (LAN, VPN) must supply a valid `X-API-Key`. If `api_key` is not set in config and the host is bound to `0.0.0.0`, all LAN requests get 403 rather than silently passing.\n\nThis mirrors the default bind: `127.0.0.1` is safe without auth; `0.0.0.0` is opt-in and requires a key."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/static/index.html",
      "line": 1774,
      "pattern": "textContent — never innerHTML",
      "title": "13 · WebUI: textContent, never innerHTML",
      "description": "All API-sourced content is written to the DOM via `element.textContent`, never `element.innerHTML`. `textContent` treats the value as a literal string and escapes HTML automatically — the T5 (XSS) mitigation.\n\n**The clearing exception**\n\n`track.innerHTML = \"\"` appears in the resource bar rendering functions to clear a container before rebuilding it with `createElement`. Assigning an empty string to `innerHTML` is safe — there is no user-controlled content involved. The pattern is: clear with `innerHTML = \"\"`, then build with `createElement()` + `appendChild()`.\n\n**Why `createElement` + `appendChild` throughout**\n\nDynamic content across the UI — resource bars, model list rows, context-window dropdowns, option selectors — is built via `document.createElement()` + `appendChild()`, not by concatenating HTML strings. This gives the same XSS guarantee as `textContent` but allows structured DOM trees (buttons inside rows, labels alongside inputs) that a plain string cannot express. The `showError` function at line 1774 is the clearest single-line example of the pattern: a raw string from the API goes directly to `textContent`, never into markup."
    }
  ]
}
